GUIDE: https://www.sitepoint.com/angular-2-tutorial/


Node.js installed	//Version check it
node -v
npm -v

npm install -g @angular-cli //globally install the angular-cli
ng version //version check

ng new app_name //init app, and create needed directories
ng serve //local development server on http://localhost:4200/

//Creates a 'todo' class w/ --spec for unit testingc
ng generate class Todo --spec 

ng test // Run the unit tests (Karma/Jasmine)

ng generate service TodoData //Creates a service
ng generate component ______ //Creates a component adds values to app.module.ts automatically as well.

Services registered in AppModule are available to all components in the entire application.

For css add the css folder under assets, and include in .angular-cli.json styles sheet

/************** Mock Back End REST API *********************************/
npm install json-server --save

//In root directory add a file called 'db.json' with the following....
{
  "todos": [
    {
      "id": 1,
      "title": "Read SitePoint article",
      "complete": false
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "title": "Clean inbox",
      "complete": false
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "title": "Make restaurant reservation",
      "complete": false
    }
  ]
} 

//And then add a script to package.json to start the back end...
"scripts": {
  ...
  "json-server": "json-server --watch db.json"
}

//Run the json server
npm run json-server

//Now check that it is running correctly...
http://localhost:3000

Angular supports the dev and prod environments naturally in app/environments/___ , 
by default the dev environment is always called unless when we 'ng serve' or 
'ng build' we specify 'ng serve --environment prod' or 'ng build --environment prod'

//Creating ApiService to communicate with REST API

//Creates service, but also registers it as provider in the Angular module defined in app.module.ts
ng generate service Api --module app.module.ts





